<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Calamagrostis nutkaensis </i>is a large perennial bunchgrass with coarse leaves that are scabrous. The species grows from Siberia and subarctic North America south to the central coast of California (Clayton et al. 2002). Distribution in California is limited to habitats near the coast from the Oregon border south to San Obispo Co. Its distribution appears highly correlated with dependable moisture, including summer fog (Corbin et al. 2005). Once established on a favorably moist site, <i>C. nutkaensis </i>develops a thick litter layer that generally slows the establishment of other plant species (Ripley 1983). <br/>
<br/>
Often considered part of the coastal prairie (Bartolome 1994, Hektner and Foin 1977), the alliance occupies the coastal terraces and mixes the <i>Danthonia californica </i>and <i>Deschampsia cespitosa </i>alliances at a fine scale. The alliance also occurs in freshwater swales, depressions, and springs, mixed with other wetland herbaceous types. It forms tall grasslands on moist coastal bluffs at the southern extent of its range. On the broad scale, stands mix with forested stands of the <i>Alnus rubra </i>and <i>Picea sitchensis </i>alliances, and shrublands of the <i>Baccharis pilularis, Lupinus arboreus, Salix hookeriana, </i>and <i>Rubus </i>spp. alliances. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
