    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Af, Ai-j). Stands occur on San Bruno Mountain within the South San Francisco city limits, and the species ranges as far south as San Luis Obispo Co. Small stands at Point Lobos State Reserve and on the Monterey Peninsula may be the southernmost.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Aa-b, Ad-e, Ag-l). Stands exist in moist wind-swept coastal bluffs and wet bottoms of Sonoma Co. (Heady et al. 1977, Hektner and Foin 1977) and in coastal freshwater swamps, dune swales, and coastal bluffs of Marin Co., and further inland around springs to Mount Tamalpais (Howell 1970, Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003a). Stands that occur in moister sites are transitional to stands of <i>Carex obnupta, Juncus effusus,</i> or <i>Juncus patens</i> alliances at Navarro Point Preserve and Point Arena -Stornetta Unit of the California Coastal National Monument in Mendocino Co. (CNPS unpublished data 2020).  Plot data exist (CNPS 2005) for Fort Ross State Park, Table Bluff Ecological Area at Eel River Wildlife Area, and Trinidad State Park. Stands at Humboldt Lagoons State Park, Redwood National Park, and in the state parks in Del Norte Co. most often border <i>Alnus rubra</i> stands.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Calamagrostis nutkaensis </i>regularly becomes shaded out, transitioning to scrub or tree stands of <i>Alnus rubra, Baccharis pilularis, </i>or <i>Rubus </i>spp. alliances. Salt-laden spray inhibits the growth of woody plants on steep, exposed coastal bluffs. Most shrubs on these coastward sites tend to be shorter than the <i>C. nutkaensis, </i>so shrubs form a matrix with the grasses and herbs rather than dominating. Active burning or clearing of woody plants maintains and encourages stands. Dense stands of the native species resist non-native <i>Holcus lanatus </i>invasion (Thomsen and Dâ€™Antonio 2007). </div>
</div>

    

    

